,Recommended,566990,29120855,Posted: 8 January,all,Redbeard,"Russian Car Driver is a fun car driving game.For what it is, a cheap game being sold for 99 cents on Steam, it's great (although, I must admit, I bought it on sale for 69c).If you want to buy a game as good as Grand Theft Auto, then you've come to the wrong place - this is just a cheap game that provides some light entertainment.Don't take this game too seriously, just have some fun with it.I read a few of the reviews about the game before I bought it; and, although some people hated it, others gave it a thumbs up.So I thought that there must be some good in it - why not give it a go?The graphics are 1990's style, so there is nothing special there.And the car mechanics are just ok.However, nonetheless, I actually really enjoyed playing Russian Car Driver.I had fun driving around the Russian countryside in my indestructible little car.The occasional bear on the road adds to the Russian ambience of the game.I've smashed through piles of logs, gone flying through the air (due to deliberately bad driving), and have done lots of cross-country travelling.Great stuff!Some reviewers mentioned that the steering wasn't too responsive, so the first thing I did before playing was to maximise the steering ability in the options - so that might have helped give me a positive experience with the game.You can bash into anything with your car, and it just keeps on going.After I went through a massive mud puddle, I thought I would try driving into into a river to wash the mud off - but, doh, it turns out that doing so was a bridge too far, and the car had to be rescued (whilst you can't drive for too long in water, I have managed to quickly drive across a river and survive).Naturally, if you bash into solid objects (such as trees or houses) you will come to a complete stop (but your car can just drive off again).If you are going fast enough, you can pretty much smash through anything else (e.g. fences, piles of logs, animals).If you speed past a cop car, they will give chase; but you can pretty much always get away from them really easily (I got caught only once, when I made a mistake and crashed directly into a police vehicle).You can speed across country. I haven't noticed any difference in the speed you can attain on the roads or in the fields - which, obviously, is unrealistic, but it all adds to the fun of the game.I've even driven up to the top of the hills/mountains which are the barriers for the edge of the map, just for a bit of amusement.However, be careful of the big slabs of rock which appear in fields, as I got myself stuck on rock formations twice in the game, so I am assuming it can happen to other players too.There are missions to be done.When you complete a mission, you can upgrade aspects of your car, such as speed and steering.There is also a radio that you can play whilst driving around, although the music is a bit blah - but it does have half a dozen radio stations to choose from.You need to turn down the other in-game sounds to be able to hear the radio better.It would be great if you could import your own music into the radio (although you could just play your own music on another programme whilst the game is running, I suppose).The radio list includes a Russian station, so there's another addition to the Russian ambience.I had a lot of fun with this - loved it!There is definitely more than 99 cents worth of fun in this game.Russian Car Driver is not meant to be on par with the top-grade racing or car driving games on the market, so just enjoy it for what it is - a good bit of fun."
